<TITLE> Turk Cypriot leader makes rare foray to Greek south </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NICOSIA, April 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Turkish Cypriot leader Mehmet Ali Talat crossed a newly opened checkpoint that has separated Greeks and Turks on the island for decades, a signal of warming ties between the two communities. The street reopened on April 3 after almost half a century of being barricaded, an enduring symbol of the divided capital, whose Greek and Turkish Cypriot quarters are separated by a U.N. buffer zone. "I can't remember the last time I came ... in my childhood maybe," Talat said as he crossed into the Greek Cypriot sector of Ledra Street. Talat, who said he crossed over on the spur of the moment, was welcomed by scores of Greek Cypriots who emerged from their shops in the teeming commercial area to shake his hand. "I want to convey my best wishes to everyone," said Talat, who spoke to shopkeepers in English and in Greek. "I don't know the place; it's almost like it is my first time here." Ledra's opening has been heralded as a welcome step towards ending the island's division, an obstacle to Turkey's membership of the European Union and a source of tension between NATO partners Athens and Ankara. "All our efforts are going for a solution, with a solution we will not need crossing points. I prefer to solve the Cyprus problem," said Talat. Cyprus's ethnic Greek and Turks have lived divided since a Turkish invasion in 1974 triggered by a brief Greek inspired coup. Countless attempts at reconciliation have collapsed. The climate for reunification has warmed considerably since the election of Greek Cypriot leader Demetris Christofias to the Cypriot presidency in February. Christofias and Talat have agreed to resume reunification talks by the end of Ju
